<span class="pill">SAFE SLEEP</span>
<h1>When Can Baby Sleep With a Blanket? NHS Guidance</h1>
<p class="subtitle">The answer is 12 months minimum – here's the safer alternative UK parents use.</p>
<div class="meta">Written by Mark, Belfast dad of two • Checked against NHS and Lullaby Trust • Last updated 17 April 2026</div>
<div class="disclosure"><strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> As an Amazon Associate we earn from qualifying purchases. <strong>Medical information:</strong> This article summarises publicly available guidance from the NHS and Lullaby Trust. It is not medical advice. Always consult your health visitor, midwife or GP.</div>

<div class="warning">
<p><strong>NHS and Lullaby Trust guidance:</strong> No blankets, duvets, quilts or pillows for babies under 12 months. Use a baby sleep bag instead.</p>
</div>

<p>Our health visitor in Belfast was very clear about loose bedding risks. UK guidance is consistent across NHS and Lullaby Trust, yet many high street shops still sell "newborn blanket sets". According to published safe sleep guidance, these should not be used for unsupervised sleep under 12 months.</p>

<h2>When can baby have a blanket NHS?</h2>
<p>According to NHS guidance, the minimum age is 12 months. The Lullaby Trust, the UK's leading safe sleep charity, states the same: no loose bedding including blankets until at least the first birthday.</p>
<p>This guidance exists because babies develop the ability to move bedding away from their face between 9-12 months, but this varies by child. Waiting until 12 months ensures most babies can roll both ways, sit up, and deliberately push objects away.</p>

<h2>Why blankets are not recommended under 12 months</h2>
<p>NHS and Lullaby Trust identify several risks with loose bedding:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Suffocation risk:</strong> Baby wriggles during sleep, blanket can cover face. Babies under 9-12 months may not have the strength or coordination to remove it</li>
<li><strong>Overheating:</strong> Lullaby Trust lists overheating as a known risk factor for SIDS. Blankets trap heat and cannot be kicked off reliably by young babies</li>
<li><strong>Entanglement:</strong> Limbs can become wrapped in loose fabric</li>
<li><strong>Inconsistent temperature:</strong> Blanket falls off, baby gets cold and wakes, leading to parents adding more layers</li>
</ul>

<div class="note">Even "cellular blankets" with holes are not recommended by NHS for babies under 12 months. The holes do not eliminate suffocation risk according to safe sleep guidance.</div>

<h2>Can my 6 month old sleep with a cellular blanket?</h2>
<p>No. NHS guidance does not make exceptions for cellular blankets, knitted blankets, or muslins used as covers. The recommendation is clear: no loose bedding under 12 months regardless of material.</p>
<p>At 6 months, many babies are starting to roll and move more, which actually increases the risk of becoming tangled or covered. This is why sleep bags are specifically recommended.</p>

<h2>What to use instead – baby sleep bags</h2>
<p>NHS specifically recommends baby sleep bags (also called baby sleeping bags or grobags) as the safer alternative. We used them for both our children from birth to age 2.</p>
<p>Benefits highlighted in guidance:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cannot cover baby's face or head</li>
<li>Provides consistent warmth all night</li>
<li>Available in different TOG ratings for room temperature – see our <a href="/posts/tog-ratings-made-simple.html">TOG ratings guide</a></li>
<li>Baby cannot kick off and become cold</li>
<li>Reduces risk of climbing out of cot later</li>
</ul>
<p>We used the <a href="https://amzn.to/4sqq7QT" target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored">Tommee Tippee Grobag</a> in 2.5 TOG for winter (room 16-18°C) and 1.0 TOG for summer. It meets the British safety standard BS EN 16781:2018 referenced in UK guidance.</p>

<h2>What age is actually safe for blankets?</h2>
<p><strong>12 months:</strong> Absolute minimum according to guidance, only if baby can roll both ways, sit up unaided, and deliberately pull blanket off face.</p>
<p><strong>18 months+:</strong> Considered safer by many health visitors. Most UK parents wait until toddler bed transition around 18-24 months.</p>
<p><strong>Our experience:</strong> We introduced a light cellular blanket at 20 months, used over the sleep bag in winter. The test was whether our child could pull it off and ask for it back – showing deliberate control.</p>

<h2>When can baby have a duvet UK?</h2>
<p>Duvets carry higher risk than blankets due to greater warmth and weight. Lullaby Trust guidance suggests waiting until at least 18 months to 2 years for a duvet, and ideally until the child is in a bed rather than cot.</p>
<p>Many parents continue with sleep bags until age 3-4, then transition directly to duvet. Sleep bags are available in larger sizes up to 4-6 years.</p>

<h2>But my baby hates sleep bags</h2>
<p>This is common during transition. According to NHS guidance, persistence is important for safety. Try:</p>
<ul>
<li>Different style – some have arms, some are sleeveless, some are footless for toddlers</li>
<li>Ensure correct size – too big is unsafe and uncomfortable</li>
<li>Use for daytime naps first to build familiarity</li>
<li>Swaddle transition bags help for babies moving from swaddling at 2-3 months</li>
<li>Check TOG rating – baby may be too hot or cold. See our <a href="/posts/room-temperature-baby-nhs.html">room temperature guide</a></li>
</ul>

<h2>What about swaddling with blankets?</h2>
<p>NHS guidance on swaddling: if you choose to swaddle, use a thin cotton muslin, stop by 2-3 months or at first signs of rolling (whichever is earlier). Never swaddle over 3 months, never place swaddled baby on front or side, never use blanket over swaddle.</p>
<p>We stopped swaddling at 8 weeks and moved straight to a 2.5 TOG sleep bag – this made the 4-month sleep regression easier as there was no transition to manage later.</p>

<h2>Grandparents insisting on blankets?</h2>
<p>This is very common in the UK. Previous generations used blankets routinely. SIDS rates in the UK have fallen by over 80% since the Back to Sleep campaign in 1991, which included removing loose bedding as a key recommendation.</p>
<p>Show grandparents current guidance from <a href="https://www.lullabytrust.org.uk" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Lullaby Trust</a> or NHS website. It's not about criticising past practices, but following current evidence.</p>

<h2>When you do introduce a blanket at 12+ months</h2>
<p>According to safe sleep guidance for toddlers:</p>
<ul>
<li>Use light cellular blanket only, not heavy quilt or duvet initially</li>
<li>Tuck in firmly at foot of bed, no higher than chest level</li>
<li>Keep baby's feet to foot of cot (feet-to-foot position)</li>
<li>Ensure baby can easily push blanket away</li>
<li>Continue to avoid pillows until 12 months minimum</li>
</ul>

<h2>Room temperature matters more than blankets</h2>
<p>Many parents want to use blankets because the room feels cold. NHS guidance recommends fixing the room temperature rather than adding bedding. Keep room between 16-20°C and use correct TOG sleep bag.</p>
<p>We used a simple digital thermometer at cot height. Our Belfast house was 17°C overnight in winter – a 2.5 TOG sleep bag with vest and sleepsuit was sufficient, no blanket needed.</p>

